        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The WINGS optical spectra have shown that ~43% (1243 objects out of 2869) of the galaxies have SFR&gt;0. The range of measured SFR is 0-2.5 Msun yr^-1. These values have been derived from the measured emission lines of Hbeta and Halpha and the spectral synthesis models. The spectra were obtained in fibers of 2 arcsec diameter. According to our adopted cosmology (H0=70, Omega_m=0.27, Omega_L=0.73) these values correspond to a SFR density (SFRD) of 0-1.5 Msun yr^-1 kpc^2. Using the standard Schmidt-Kennitutt (1998) law, these values of the SFRD imply a range of molecular gas density between 0-300 Msun pc^-2 (corresponding to H2 molecular masses between 10^6-10^10 Msun).
The CO fluxes in Jy km sec^1 were then obtained through eq. (5) of Casasola et al. (2004) assuming a constant CO-H2 conversion factor
of 2.3x10^20 mol cm^-2 (K km sec^-1). We got CO fluxes from 0-1.3 Jy km sec^-1. We then divide for the FWHM of the CO line (~300 km sec^-1) and for the sky area of the fiber beam (2 arcsec) getting CO line flux densities between 0-1.7 mJy arcsec^-2. Assuming a S/N ratio of at least 5 for the detection we get a rms sensitivity between 0-1.5 in a beam of 2 arcsec.

Our spiral targets have measured SFRs of 0.28, 0.47 and 0.98 Msun yr^-1, which correspond, according to the previous calculation, to a 5 sigma sensitivity of 0.28, 0.42 and 0.59 mJy.
We have therefore chosen a detection sensitivity of 0.28 mJy in a beam of 2 arcsec, that coupled with a spectral bandwidth of 100 km sec^-1, provide a total exposure time on source of ~2 hours. Taking into account overheads we get a total time of ~4 hours.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
