    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose a one shot ALMA observation of three spiral galaxies members of the Abell cluster A2399. This is a pilot study aiming at proving the detection of the CO(1-0) line emission in normal galaxies at distances of ~250 Mpc, if their SFR &gt; 0.1 Msun/yr. According to our calculation these observations are possible with ALMA, either in term of sensitivity that of spatial resolution. However, the feasibility largely depends on the present uncertainties on the Schimdt-Kennicutt'law, on the CO-H2 conversion factor and on the dust-to-gas ratio. In case of a positive detection the observations of ~120 spiral members of the WINGS survey will provide in the future the data that can definitively prove or disprove the quenching of star formation due to the environment. In the negative case, we can check which hypothesis failed and calculate upper limits for the global CO content of our galaxies. These values are also important for assessing the depletion of CO in cluster spirals.</prp:abstract>
